{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478582"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17522"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17522"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.02,0.03,0.01,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109156"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10212"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91515"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"1823"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36592"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40753"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109156"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parent due to a large bruise on his forehead after falling while learning to walk. The bruise appeared immediately after the fall six hours ago. He has no loss of consciousness or vomiting. His parent mentions he has had two episodes of spontaneous swelling and pain in his knee joints over the past three months, and had prolonged bleeding after his routine vaccinations. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. There is a family history of bleeding problems in male family members on his mother\u0027s side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 5 cm bruise on his forehead without swelling or tenderness. The remainder of his examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActivated Partial Thromboplastin Time: 89 seconds (25-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProthrombin Time: 12 seconds (11-13)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["von Willebrand factor studies","Platelet function assay","Bleeding time","Platelet aggregometry","Factor VIII assay"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic presentation of haemophilia with spontaneous haemarthroses, prolonged bleeding after procedures, and an isolated prolongation of activated Partial Thromboplastin Time (aPTT). The family history of bleeding in male relatives on the maternal side strongly suggests an X-linked bleeding disorder. Given the clinical presentation and coagulation studies, the most likely diagnosis is haemophilia A, which would be confirmed by a \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor VIII assay\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Evon Willebrand factor studies\u003C/strong\u003E would be less likely as the primary investigation, although von Willebrand disease can occasionally present with prolonged aPTT. However, von Willebrand disease typically presents with mucocutaneous bleeding rather than haemarthroses, is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, and affects males and females equally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet function assay\u003C/strong\u003E would be used to investigate platelet dysfunction as a cause of bleeding, but the clinical presentation suggests coagulation factor deficiency rather than platelet dysfunction. Additionally, platelet disorders would not cause isolated aPTT prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBleeding time\u003C/strong\u003E is an outdated test that has been replaced by more specific coagulation studies and platelet function tests. It would not provide specific diagnostic information about the underlying factor deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelet aggregometry\u003C/strong\u003E would be used to assess platelet function and aggregation responses, but this would not explain the isolated aPTT prolongation or the pattern of bleeding consistent with a coagulation factor deficiency rather than platelet dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe bleeding pattern helps distinguish between coagulation factor deficiency and platelet disorders:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable\u003E\u003Ctbody\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFeature\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECoagulation Factor Deficiency\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet Disorders\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBleeding pattern\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDeep bleeding (haemarthroses, muscle haematomas)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuperficial bleeding (petechiae, purpura, mucosal)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnset after trauma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMay be delayed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd colspan=\u00221\u0022 rowspan=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOften immediate bleeding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/tbody\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFactor VIII assay is the most appropriate confirmatory test as haemophilia A (Factor VIII deficiency) is the most common X-linked inherited bleeding disorder, affecting approximately 1 in 5,000 male births and accounting for about 80% of haemophilia cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemophilia A (Factor VIII deficiency) is more common than Haemophilia B (Factor IX deficiency) and both are inherited in an X-linked recessive pattern.","Spontaneous haemarthroses are characteristic of haemophilia and distinguish it from other bleeding disorders like von Willebrand disease.","Factor VIII and IX assays are required to differentiate between haemophilia A and B when coagulation studies show isolated prolonged aPTT."],"references":["Bertamino M, Riccardi F, Banov L, Svahn J, Molinari AC. Hemophilia Care in the Pediatric Age. J Clin Med. 2017 May 19;6(5):54. doi: 10.3390/jcm6050054. PMID: 28534860; PMCID: PMC5447945."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91515"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17522"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91515"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-18T16:55:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-18T16:56:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10212"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109156"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"